Prevention Program 3 Description



This process includes three interconnected production units, Lube Oil Distillation, Lube Oil Hydrotreater and MS142.  Everything in this prevention program applies to all three units.



Process Description:  Process ID: 1000090778 ? Re-Refinery ? Includes VLO Distillation Unit, Hydrotreater, MS142, Utilities and Onsite Tankage.



Re-Refinery lube oil process, with a maximum capacity of 75 million gallons per year, and consisting of:



1)  Lube Oil Distillation, identified as P-400, used to remove water, light fuels, and heavy hydrocarbons from the used oil feed stream; producing two overhead streams, which include a water/light fuel stream and an off-gas stream, and byproducts vacuum lube oil and asphalt, consisting of:

(a) Natural gas-fired boiler, identified as SB-201, constructed in 2018, with a maximum capacity of 16.33 MMBtu/hr, and exhausting through stack SB-201;

(b) Vacuum heater, constructed in 2010, approved for modification in 2012, fueled by natural gas during normal operation, and process stream offgases during start-up or shut-down of H-401/402, H-500, or H-501 or during HT start of run conditions, identified as H-400, with a maximum capacity of

25.00 MMBtu/hr, and exhausting through stack H-400;

(c) Dehydration heater, approved for construction in 2012, fueled by a combination of natural gas, vaporized distillate fuel, dehydration off-gas, sour water, and HT off-gas during HT start of run reactor conditions and HT startup and shutdown, identified as H-402, with a maximum capacity of 60 MMBtu/hr, and exhausting through stack H-402;

(d) Back-up dehydration heater, constructed in 2010, fueled by a combination of natural gas, vaporized distillate fuel, dehydration off-gas, sour water, and HT off-gas during HT start of run reactor conditions and HT startup and shutdown, identified as H-401, with a maximum capacity of 36.0 MMBtu/hr, and exhausting through stack H-401. H-401 will be used only during instances of H-402 downtime.

(e) Caustic scrubber, identified as V-403, used to remove H2S from P-400 and MS142 off-gasses, prior to entering Vacuum Heater H-400 and Dehydration Heater H-401;

(f) Lube Oil Distillation Unit and ancillary equipment, and;

(g) Vacuum system used to collect and transfer off-gas from P-400 to V- 403 or back to P-400.



2)  Lube Oil Hydrotreater (HT), identified as P-500, used to improve the quality of lube oil as a finished product, consisting of:

(a) A series of reactors, to remove nitrogen, oxygen, sulfur, chlorine, and other contaminants;

(b) Process heater, constructed in 2011, approved for modification in 2012, combusting natural gas, VLO and Dehy off-gas during normal operation, and VLO off-gas during start-up or shut-down of H-401/402,  identified as H-500, with a nominal rating of 17.00 MMBtu/hr, used to heat the P-500 reactor feeds, and exhausting through stack H-500;

(c) Process heater, constructed in 2011, approved for modification in 2012, combusting natural gas and HT off-gas during normal operation, and VLO off-gas during start-up and shutdown of H-401/H-402, identified as H-501, with a nominal rating of 7.00 MMBtu/hr, used to heat the P-500 reactor feeds, and exhausting through stack H-501;

(d) Caustic scrubber, identified as T-501, used to remove H2S from of the hydrogen rich recycle gas used in the reactors.

(e) Natural gas process heater, identified as H-502, constructed in 2011, with a nominal rating of 8.14 MMBtu/hr, used to preheat the P-500 reactor feed to the steam stripper column, and exhausting through

stack H-502; (vi) One (1) steam stripper column, identified as T-500, and associated ancillary equipment, used to remove light fuels or off-gas;

(f) Air dryers, identified as T-502 and T-503, used to cool and dry the steam stripper bottoms product, exhausting through stacks T-502 and T-503, respectively;

(g) High pressure separator, identified as V-501;

(h) Low pressure caustic flash drum, identified as V-502;

(i) Off-gas knock out, identified as V-505;

(j) Caustic cooler heat exchanger, identified as E-503; and

(k) Caustic scrubber, identified as V-510, used to remove H2S from the HT off-gas stream prior to combustion in Heaters H-500 and H-501.



3) MS142 - Clean mineral spirits operation, identified as P-100, constructed in 2007, with a maximum capacity of 6,000 gallons per hour, processing mineral spirits to produce clean solvents, residue, and light fuel, utilizing no control devices, and exhausting to the ambient air, and consisting of:

(a) One (1) natural gas-fired boiler, identified as S8-200, with a maximum capacity of 14.645 MM8tu/hr, and exhausting through stack S8-200.

(b) One (1) Distillation Column and associated ancillary equipment, identified asMS142.

(c) One (1) Vacuum system used to collect and transfer off-gas from MS142 to T-102.



Utilities include production equipment and distribution systems for steam, instrument air and nitrogen for operation of the refinery.



Onsite tankage consists of thirty-seven tanks used to support refinery feed, intermediate processing and final product storage and shipping.

Operations comply with OSHA Standard 29 CFR 1910.119, Process Safety Management of highly hazardous chemicals via Corporate and Local management?s commitment to the elements of PSM by applying the programs and policies found in the standard to activities throughout the facility. Specific program elements include:

1. Employee Participation ? It is the policy of Heritage Crystal-Clean (HCC) to seek participation of employees at all levels in establishing procedures and practices that govern Health, Safety and Environmental issues.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Employee Participation element is implemented in HSEL0038; 

2. Process Safety Information ? Process safety information is maintained for the facility.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Process Safety Information element is implemented in HSEL0039; 

3. Process Hazard Analysis ? A detailed process hazard assessment, using HAZOP, is conducted on the facility to insure that it has been designed safely.  The PSM   Policy includes a description of how the Process Hazard Analysis element is implemented in HSES0246; 

4. Operating Procedures ? A system is in place to ensure that updated and approved procedures cover the facility's operation.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Operating Procedure element is implemented in HSEL0040; 

5. Training ? A training program has been established to ensure that personnel are well trained in the specific duties of their jobs (The process also includes an annual Training Needs Analysis).  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Training element is implemented in HSES0460; 

6. Contractors ? It is HCC's objective to partner with contractors that share the same safety philosophy.  A dedicated, collective, and consistent approach by HCC and contractors will enhance and maintain the safety and health of our respective employees.  The PSM Contractor Management Program element is included in HSES0857; 

